Dynamic quenching was caused by charge transfer or energy transfer. In order to identify the origin, we performed XPS analysis of AIS QDs in the presence of Pb2+ (Fig. 15
                        ). C 1s peak for referencing was set at 285.1 eV. Compared with XPS spectra of AIS QDs without Pb2+, there were no obvious changes in binding energies of Ag 3d, In 3d and S 2p (Fig. 15A–C). Fig. 15D showed that the peaks located at 142.1 eV and 136.6 eV were attributed to Pb 4f5/2 and 4f 7/2, indicating that the valence of lead element was zero. Hence, we inferred that Pb2+ quenching the fluorescence of AIS QDs was owing to the electron transfer, and the possible mechanism was schemed in Fig. 16
                        . The production of AIS QDs fluorescence was the result of photo-generated electron-hole recombination. When AIS QDs were irradiated, the photo-generated electrons of AIS QDs were captured by Pb2+, causing the electron-hole pairs failed to recombine, leading to the fluorescence quenching of AIS QDs. Therefore, the possible fluorescent quenching mechanism of AIS QDs by Pb2+ was the dynamic quenching mechanism of light-induced electron transfer.
